{
  "A 5 kg block is pushed with a net force of 20 N. What is its acceleration?": "",
  "2 m/s²": "",
  "4 m/s²": "",
  "100 m/s²": "",
  "10 m/s²": "",
  "Using Newton's second law: a = F_net/m = 20/5 = 4 m/s².": "",
  "Two forces of 8 N and 6 N act on an object at right angles. What is the magnitude of the net force?": "",
  "14 N": "",
  "48 N": "",
  "10 N": "",
  "2 N": "",
  "For perpendicular forces, F_net = sqrt(8² + 6²) = sqrt(64 + 36) = sqrt(100) = 10 N.": "",
  "A 10 kg object is in free fall. What is the net force acting on it? (Use g = 9.8 m/s²)": "",
  "0 N": "",
  "98 N": "",
  "49 N": "",
  "In free fall the only force is gravity: F = mg = 10(9.8) = 98 N downward.": "",
  "A 3 kg block on a frictionless surface is pulled by a rope with 12 N of tension at 30° above horizontal. What is the horizontal acceleration?": "",
  "4.0 m/s²": "",
  "6.0 m/s²": "",
  "3.46 m/s²": "",
  "2.0 m/s²": "",
  "Horizontal force component: F_x = 12cos30° = 12(0.866) = 10.39 N. Acceleration: a = 10.39/3 ≈ 3.46 m/s².": "",
  "An Atwood machine has masses of 6 kg and 4 kg. What is the acceleration of the system? (Use g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "1 m/s²": "",
  "5 m/s²": "",
  "For an Atwood machine: a = (m₁ - m₂)g/(m₁ + m₂) = (6 - 4)(10)/(6 + 4) = 20/10 = 2 m/s².": "",
  "A force F(t) = 6t (in Newtons) acts on a 2 kg object initially at rest. What is the velocity at t = 4 s?": "",
  "12 m/s": "",
  "24 m/s": "",
  "48 m/s": "",
  "6 m/s": "",
  "a(t) = F/m = 3t. v = integral from 0 to 4 of 3t dt = (3/2)t² evaluated from 0 to 4 = (3/2)(16) = 24 m/s.": "",
  "A 1000 kg elevator accelerates upward at 2 m/s². What is the tension in the cable? (Use g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "10,000 N": "",
  "8,000 N": "",
  "2,000 N": "",
  "12,000 N": "",
  "T - mg = ma, so T = m(g + a) = 1000(10 + 2) = 12,000 N.": "",
  "A 2 kg block on a frictionless incline at 30° slides down. What is its acceleration? (Use g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "8.66 m/s²": "",
  "2.5 m/s²": "",
  "On a frictionless incline: a = g sin θ = 10 sin 30° = 10(0.5) = 5 m/s².": "",
  "A person stands on a scale in an elevator. The scale reads 800 N at rest. What does it read when accelerating downward at 3 m/s²? (Use g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "560 N": "",
  "240 N": "",
  "800 N": "",
  "1040 N": "",
  "Mass = 800/10 = 80 kg. During downward acceleration: N = m(g - a) = 80(10 - 3) = 80(7) = 560 N.": "",
  "Three blocks (2 kg, 3 kg, 5 kg) are connected by massless strings and pulled by a 50 N horizontal force on a frictionless surface. What is the system's acceleration?": "",
  "25 m/s²": "",
  "Total mass = 2 + 3 + 5 = 10 kg. a = F/m_total = 50/10 = 5 m/s².": "",
  "What is Newton's first law of motion?": "",
  "The momentum of a system is always conserved": "",
  "Force equals mass times acceleration": "",
  "For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction": "",
  "An object at rest stays at rest and an object in motion stays in uniform motion unless acted upon by a net external force": "",
  "Newton's first law (law of inertia) states that an object maintains its state of rest or uniform motion in a straight line unless a net external force acts on it.": "",
  "What does Newton's second law state in its most general form?": "",
  "F = ma, applicable only when mass is constant": "",
  "The net force equals the time rate of change of momentum: F_net = dp/dt": "",
  "Every force has an equal and opposite reaction force": "",
  "Objects in equilibrium have zero velocity": "",
  "Newton's second law in its general form is F_net = dp/dt, which reduces to F = ma when mass is constant. This form handles variable-mass systems like rockets.": "",
  "What is an inertial reference frame?": "",
  "A reference frame in which Newton's laws of motion are valid, one that is not accelerating": "",
  "A reference frame that is accelerating at a constant rate": "",
  "Any frame in which an observer is at rest": "",
  "A frame attached to the center of mass of a system": "",
  "An inertial reference frame is one that is not accelerating or rotating, where Newton's laws hold without the need for fictitious forces.": "",
  "What is a free-body diagram?": "",
  "A graph of force versus time for an object": "",
  "A sketch of all objects in a physical system and their connections": "",
  "A diagram showing the trajectory of a free-falling object": "",
  "A diagram that shows all the external forces acting on a single isolated object": "",
  "A free-body diagram isolates a single object and represents all external forces acting on it as arrows, which is essential for applying Newton's second law.": "",
  "What does the term 'net force' mean?": "",
  "The largest force acting on an object": "",
  "The force required to keep an object at rest": "",
  "The force remaining after friction is subtracted": "",
  "The vector sum of all forces acting on an object": "",
  "Net force is the vector sum of all individual forces acting on an object. It determines the object's acceleration via F_net = ma.": "",
  "What is Newton's third law?": "",
  "The acceleration of an object is proportional to the net force applied": "",
  "Forces always come in balanced pairs that cancel each other out": "",
  "When one object exerts a force on a second object, the second simultaneously exerts a force equal in magnitude and opposite in direction on the first": "",
  "An object at rest tends to stay at rest": "",
  "Newton's third law states that forces always come in action-reaction pairs that act on different objects, are equal in magnitude, and opposite in direction.": "",
  "What is meant by 'equilibrium' in dynamics?": "",
  "When an object is at rest": "",
  "When the net force on an object is zero, resulting in zero acceleration": "",
  "When an object moves in a circle at constant speed": "",
  "When all forces acting on an object are equal": "",
  "An object is in equilibrium when the vector sum of all forces is zero, meaning zero acceleration. It can be at rest or moving at constant velocity.": "",
  "What does 'tension' refer to in the context of forces?": "",
  "The resistance force opposing motion through a fluid": "",
  "The pulling force transmitted through a string, rope, cable, or similar connector": "",
  "The force due to gravity acting on a suspended mass": "",
  "The force exerted by a compressed spring": "",
  "Tension is the pulling force transmitted axially through a flexible connector like a string or rope, directed along its length away from the object.": "",
  "What is meant by 'normal force'?": "",
  "The contact force exerted by a surface perpendicular to the surface, preventing objects from passing through": "",
  "The horizontal component of any applied force": "",
  "The gravitational force between two objects": "",
  "The force that always equals the weight of an object": "",
  "The normal force is the perpendicular contact force a surface exerts on an object. It is not always equal to mg and adjusts based on other forces present.": "",
  "What does 'inertia' mean in physics?": "",
  "The force that keeps objects at rest": "",
  "The energy stored in a moving object": "",
  "The tendency of an object to resist changes in its state of motion, quantified by its mass": "",
  "The momentum of an object at rest": "",
  "Inertia is the property of matter that resists changes in motion. Mass is the quantitative measure of inertia: greater mass means greater resistance to acceleration.": "",
  "A 70 kg skydiver experiences a drag force of F_drag = 0.25v² (Newtons). What is the terminal velocity? (Use g = 9.8 m/s²)": "",
  "Approximately 28 m/s": "",
  "Approximately 69 m/s": "",
  "Approximately 52 m/s": "",
  "Approximately 37 m/s": "",
  "At terminal velocity, mg = 0.25v², so v = sqrt(mg/0.25) = sqrt(70 x 9.8/0.25) = sqrt(2744) ≈ 52.4 m/s.": "",
  "An aerospace engineer designs a rocket of mass 5000 kg that must achieve a minimum liftoff acceleration of 15 m/s². What minimum thrust is required? (Use g = 9.8 m/s²)": "",
  "99,000 N": "",
  "124,000 N": "",
  "49,000 N": "",
  "75,000 N": "",
  "F_thrust - mg = ma, so F_thrust = m(g + a) = 5000(9.8 + 15) = 5000(24.8) = 124,000 N.": "",
  "In a physics lab, two blocks (m₁ = 4 kg on a frictionless table, m₂ = 1 kg hanging off the edge via a pulley) are connected by a light string. What is the acceleration and the tension in the string? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "a = 2 m/s², T = 8 N": "",
  "a = 10 m/s², T = 0 N": "",
  "a = 2.5 m/s², T = 7.5 N": "",
  "a = 5 m/s², T = 5 N": "",
  "a = m₂g/(m₁ + m₂) = 1(10)/(4 + 1) = 2 m/s². T = m₁a = 4(2) = 8 N.": "",
  "A 1200 kg car traveling at 25 m/s must stop in 50 m. What braking force is required, and what minimum coefficient of friction is needed? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "F = 3750 N, μ = 0.3125": "",
  "F = 15000 N, μ = 1.25": "",
  "F = 6000 N, μ = 0.50": "",
  "F = 7500 N, μ = 0.625": "",
  "v² = v₀² + 2aΔx: 0 = 625 - 2a(50), a = 6.25 m/s². F = ma = 1200(6.25) = 7500 N. μ = a/g = 6.25/10 = 0.625.": "",
  "A construction worker pulls a 50 kg crate up a 20° frictionless ramp using a rope parallel to the ramp. What force is needed to accelerate the crate at 1 m/s² up the ramp? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "171 N": "",
  "50 N": "",
  "221 N": "",
  "500 N": "",
  "Along the ramp: F - mg sin20° = ma. F = 50(1) + 50(10)(sin20°) = 50 + 500(0.342) = 50 + 171 = 221 N.": "",
  "A variable force F(t) = 10 - 2t (Newtons) is applied to a 5 kg object at rest. At what time does the object reach maximum velocity, and what is that velocity?": "",
  "t = 5 s, v = 10 m/s": "",
  "t = 2.5 s, v = 2.5 m/s": "",
  "t = 5 s, v = 5 m/s": "",
  "t = 10 s, v = 10 m/s": "",
  "Maximum velocity occurs when F = 0: 10 - 2t = 0, t = 5 s. v = integral from 0 to 5 of (10-2t)/5 dt = [2t - 0.2t²] from 0 to 5 = 10 - 5 = 5 m/s.": "",
  "A child of mass 30 kg on a swing moves at 4 m/s at the bottom of the arc. If the rope length is 2 m, what is the tension at that point? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "540 N": "",
  "300 N": "",
  "420 N": "",
  "At the bottom: T - mg = mv²/r. T = mg + mv²/r = 30(10) + 30(16)/2 = 300 + 240 = 540 N.": "",
  "A package on a conveyor belt starts from rest. The belt moves at 3 m/s and the coefficient of static friction is 0.4. How far does the package travel before matching the belt's speed? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "2.25 m": "",
  "1.125 m": "",
  "0.45 m": "",
  "0.75 m": "",
  "Friction accelerates the package: a = μg = 0.4(10) = 4 m/s². Using v² = 2ad: 9 = 2(4)d, d = 9/8 = 1.125 m.": "",
  "A 2000 kg truck drives onto a bridge that can withstand 30,000 N of force. The truck hits a bump that launches it briefly upward, then it lands. If the truck's tires compress 0.05 m on landing from a height of 0.2 m, what average force does the bridge experience? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "100,000 N": "",
  "60,000 N": "",
  "98,000 N": "",
  "Landing speed: v = sqrt(2gh) = sqrt(2(10)(0.2)) = 2 m/s. Deceleration over 0.05 m: a = v²/(2d) = 4/0.1 = 40 m/s². Force = m(g+a) = 2000(50) = 100,000 N, well exceeding the bridge limit.": "",
  "A firefighter (80 kg) slides down a vertical pole. She grips the pole to produce a friction force and wants to descend 15 m in exactly 3 seconds starting from rest. What friction force must she maintain? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "533 N": "",
  "267 N": "",
  "400 N": "",
  "Required acceleration: 15 = ½a(9), a = 30/9 = 10/3 m/s² downward. mg - f = ma: 800 - f = 80(10/3) = 267 N, so f = 800 - 267 = 533 N.": ""
